'''Antera Duke''' (alive as late as 1788) was an 18th-century African [[slavery|slave]] dealer and [[Efik people|Efik]] chief from [[Calabar]] in eastern [[Nigeria]] (now in [[Cross River State]]). His diary, written in [[Nigerian Pidgin English]], was discovered in [[Scotland]] and published. This diary records his interactions with British merchants to whom he sold slaves; he writes about wearing "white man trousers" and entertaining the merchants he traded with.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/abolition/slavery_business_gallery_12.shtml|title= The Business of Enslavement |accessdate=2007-12-26 |last=Pocock |first=Nigel |author2=Victoria Cook |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref>
==References== <references/>
==Further reading== *C. Dayll Forde (ed.), Efik Traders of Old Calabar (London: Oxford University Press, 1956) (contains Duke's diary)
