{{ infobox nobility | name = Gilbert fitz Gilbert de Clare | image = Seal of Gilbert Fitz Gilbert de Clare, Earl of Pembroke.jpg | image_size = 150px | caption = Seal of Gilbert fitz Gilbert, from [[Lansdowne MS.]] 203 | noble family = de Clare | father = [[Gilbert Fitz Richard]] | mother = Alice de Claremont | spouse = Isabel de Beaumont | birth_date = {{circa|1100}} | birth_place = [[Tonbridge]] | death_date = {{death date|1148|1|6|df=y}} | death_place = }}
'''Gilbert fitz Gilbert de Clare''' ({{circa|1100}}{{snd}}6 January 1148), was created [[Earl of Pembroke]] in 1138.<ref group=lower-alpha>He was called 'Strongbow' but his son Richard is much more readily associated with that nickname.</ref>
==Life== Born at [[Tonbridge]], Gilbert de Clare was a son of [[Gilbert Fitz Richard|Gilbert Fitz Richard de Clare]] and Alice de Claremont.<ref>George Edward Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage; or, A History of the House of Lords and All its Members from the Earliest Times'', Vol. X, Eds. H. A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, & Howard de Walden (London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., 1945), p. 348</ref> He started out without land and wealth of his own but was closely related to very powerful men, specifically his uncles [[Walter de Clare]] and Roger de Clare.<ref>David Walker, ''Medieval Wales'' (Cambridge University Press, 1999), p. 40</ref>
In 1136 Gilbert fitz Gilbert led an expedition against [[Exmes]] and burned parts of the town, including the church of Notre Dame, but was interrupted by the forces of [[William III, Count of Ponthieu]] and escaped the resulting melee only after suffering heavy losses.<ref>George Edward Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage; or, A History of the House of Lords and All its Members from the Earliest Times'', Vol. X, Eds. H. A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, & Howard de Walden (London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., 1945), p. 348, & footnote (a)</ref> Gilbert was a Baron, that is, a [[tenant-in-chief]] in England, and inherited the estates of his paternal uncles, Roger and Walter, which included the baronies and castles of Bienfaite and [[Orbec]] in [[Normandy]]. He held the lordship of Nether Gwent and the castle of [[Striguil]] (later [[Chepstow Castle|Chepstow]]). [[Stephen of England|King Stephen]] created him [[Earl of Pembroke]], and gave him the [[Rape (county subdivision)|rape]] and [[Pevensey Castle|castle of Pevensey]].
After Stephen's [[Battle of Lincoln (1141)|defeat at Lincoln]] on 2 February 1141, Gilbert was among those who rallied to [[Empress Matilda]] when she recovered London in June, but he was at [[Canterbury]] when Stephen was recrowned late in 1141.<ref>J. H. Round, ''Geoffrey de Mandeville'' (Longmans, Green, 1892), p. 158</ref> He then joined Geoffrey's plot against Stephen, but when that conspiracy collapsed, he again adhered to Stephen, being with him at the siege of [[Oxford]] late in 1142. In 1147 he rebelled when Stephen refused to give him the castles surrendered by his nephew [[Gilbert Fitz Richard de Clare|Gilbert]], 2nd [[Earl of Hertford]], whereupon the King marched to his nearest castle and nearly captured him. However, the Earl appears to have made his peace with Stephen before his death the following year.<ref>Paul Dalton, Graeme J. White. ''King Stephen's Reign (1135-1154)''King Stephen's Reign (1135-1154)'' (Woodbridge: The Boydell Press, 2008), pp. 88-89</ref>
==Family== He married Isabel de Beaumont, before 1130, daughter of Sir [[Robert de Beaumont, 1st Earl of Leicester|Robert de Beaumont]], 1st [[Earl of Leicester]], Count of Meulan, and [[Elizabeth of Vermandois, Countess of Leicester|Elizabeth de Vermandois]].<ref>George Edward Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage; or, A History of the House of Lords and All its Members from the Earliest Times'', Vol. X, Eds. H. A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, & Howard de Walden (London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., 1945), p. 351</ref> Isabel had previously been the mistress of King [[Henry I of England]].<ref>George Edward Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage; or, A History of the House of Lords and All its Members from the Earliest Times'', Vol. VII, Eds. H. A. Doubleday & Howard de Walden (London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., 1929), p. 526, footnote (c)</ref>
By her Gilbert had: * [[Richard de Clare, 2nd Earl of Pembroke]]<ref group=lower-alpha>[[William Dugdale]] had credited Gilbert, the first Earl of Pembroke, with a second son who was named Baldwin fitz Gilbert; but [[J. Horace Round|Round]] showed that this Baldwin was really his brother. See: CP: X, Appendix H, p. 100.</ref><ref>George Edward Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage; or, A History of the House of Lords and All its Members from the Earliest Times'', Vol. X, Eds. H. A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, & Howard de Walden (London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., 1945), p. 352-57, Appendix H, pp. 102-04</ref> * Basilia, who married (1) [[Raymond FitzGerald]] (Raymond le Gros) and (2) Geoffrey FitzRobert.<ref>George Edward Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage; or, A History of the House of Lords and All its Members from the Earliest Times'', Vol. X, Eds. H. A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, & Howard de Walden (London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., 1945), Appendix H, p. 100</ref> * a daughter who married William Bloet.<ref>David Crouch, ''William Marshal; Court, Career and Chivalry in the Angevin Empire 1147-1219'' (London & New York: Longman, 1990), p. 139</ref>
