{{Korean name|[[Moon (Korean name)|Moon]]}} {{Infobox Politician |name = Moon Kook-hyun <!-- Commented out because image was deleted: | image = Moon Kook-hyun.jpg--> |imagesize = 200px |caption = |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|1|12|mf=y}} |birth_place = [[Seoul]], {{KOR}} |death_date = |death_place = |party = [[Creative Korea Party]] |residence = [[Eunpyeong-gu]], [[Seoul]] |occupation = |religion = Roman Catholic |relations = |spouse = Park Su-ae |children = 2 daughters |office = Leader of the [[Creative Korea Party]] |term_start = October 14, 2007 |term_end = |predecessor = Lee Jae-oh ([[Grand National Party|GNP]]) |constituency = |office2 = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Korea|National Assembly]] |term_start2 = June 5, 2008 |successor = |constituency2 = [[Eunpyeong-gu|Eunpyeong-eul]], [[Seoul]] |majority = }}
{{Infobox Korean name |img= |hangul=문국현 ||hanja={{linktext|文|國|現}} ||rr=Mun Guk-hyeon ||mr=Mun Kuk-hyŏn }}
'''Moon Kook-hyun''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: 문국현, [[Hanja]]: 文國現, born 12 January 1949) is the leader of the [[Creative Korea Party]], who served as a well-known [[Chief Executive Officer|business manager]] and civil [[Environmentalism|environmental]] campaigner in [[South Korea]] before entering his political career.
Born in [[Seoul]], Moon studied [[English language]] at the [[Hankuk University of Foreign Studies]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in 1972, then took a postgraduate course in [[Business Administration]] at the [[Seoul National University]].<ref name="chosun">"[http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200101/200101190405.html Moon Kook-hyun, CEO Of Yuhan-Kimberly] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108222757/http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200101/200101190405.html |date=2009-01-08 }}", ''[[Chosun Ilbo]]'', 19 January 2001</ref>
== As a Business Leader == Moon began his career at [[Yuhan-Kimberly]]([[:ko:유한킴벌리|유한킴벌리]]), a company manufacturing [[paper]] and woven fibre products. In 1983, he spent a year in the [[United States]], taking some new management concepts. On his return, he developed the concept of "environmental management", focusing on [[digital printing]] technologies and the use of [[recycled paper]].<ref name="chosun" />
In 1995, Moon became [[Chief Executive Officer]] of Yuhan-Kimberly. In 1996, Moon was appointed committee director of the U.N. Environment (UNEP) Korea Development Organization. Faced with a financial crisis in 1997, he developed a new [[shift work|shift]] system where workers worked twelve-hours shifts for four days running, then took four days off.<ref name="chosun" />
==2007 Presidential Election== In August 2007, Moon resigned from Yuhan-Kimberly to run in the [[South Korean presidential election, 2007]]. In October, he formed the [[Creative Korea Party]], with an [[Political corruption|anti-corruption]], pro-environmentalist program, gaining a bit of support from liberal voters who supported the [[Roh Moo-hyun|Participatory Government]], conservative voters who wanted to change the government and liked a similar 'business leader' portfolio but disliked [[Lee Myung-bak]], and from the [[labor movement]].<ref>"[http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2007/10/30/14/0301000000AEN20071030007800315F.HTML Dark horse presidential candidate launches party ahead of election]", [[Yonhap|Yonhap News Agency]], 30 October 2007</ref>
In the election, Moon won 5.8% of the votes for fourth place. Moon is a Roman Catholic.<ref>[http://www.moon21.kr/moon/profile.php 문국현 소개]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
==2008 Legislative Election== On April 9, 2008, Moon beat the close confidante of [[Lee Myung-bak]] (president) [[Lee Jae-oh]] ([[Grand National Party|GNP]], [[Incumbent]]), by more than 11%.<ref>[http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2008/04/116_22230.html Rise and Fall of Heavyweights], the Korea Times, Retrieved on April 9, 2008</ref> Although the harsh loss of South Korean liberal candidates especially in Seoul at this [[South Korean parliamentary election, 2008|2008 election]], his campaign against 'the Grand Korean Canal' project boosted his popularity in his electoral division and across the nation.
